result.execSummary:
The defendant Fredrick J Lawson Jr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Injury by Use/Vehicle-Control. Substance, a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.25(1)(am).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Fredrick J Lawson in court with attorney Michael Reyes.  Francesco Mineo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.    The Court sentenced defendant to serve 9 MONTHS in the House of Corrections, with Huber release privileges for work and treatment, with good time credit, consecutive to any other sentence.  Court STAYED sentence and placed the defendant on PROBATION for a period of 2 YEARS with the following conditions:
-Restitution set at $0
-Defendant to pay Court costs and all applicable surcharges and assessments are to be collected during term of probation;  nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment
-Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the related surcharge to be collected during term of probation; nonpayment penalty shall result in a civil judgment
-No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
-No association with drug users, drug dealers and drug houses or otherwise engage in drug dealing
-Cooperate with agent
-Obtain/maintain employment unless in school.  If in school full-time, defendant to have a part-time job 
-AODA assessment and any recommended treatment
-Absolute sobriety with random urine screens and breathalyzers
-No alcohol or controlled substances
-No driving without a valid license
-2 year drivers license revocation
-As a condition of probation, Court sentenced defendant to serve 30 DAYS in the House of Corrections, with Huber releases privileges for work and treatment.   Defendant to report to the House of Corrections on 11-27-15 at 6:00 p.m.
